ICAnet can run on both single batch and multi-batch datasets. For each datasets, we run ICA independently, further, we cluster the all independent components, find shared and specific expression programs, and combine with PPI to perform clustering. In this tutorial, I gonna used cell line dataset provided by 10X Genomics as illustate dataset to show how to use ICAnet to perform batch effect correction and clustering. The source dataset(including gene expression dataset, cell annotation, and PPI network) can be download from https://github.com/WWXkenmo/MouseGerm. We load the dataset at the first,

PPI <- readRDS("PPI_for_cell_line.RDS")
all.data <- readRDS("cell_line_exp.RDS")
ID <- read.table("ID_for_cell_line.txt",header=TRUE,row.names=1,stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

First, We convert expression dataset into Seurat object, perform normalization

all.data <- CreateSeuratObject(counts = all.data, project = "cell.all", min.cells = 0)
all.data$celltype <- ID$cell.type
all.data$batch <- ID$batch
all.data <- NormalizeData(all.data, normalization.method = "LogNormalize", scale.factor = 10000)

We noted that this expression dataset has been quality controlled. Then, we run the first step of ICAnet, which compute ICA on each batch (293t cell, jurkat cell, 50:50 mixed)

ica <- ICAcomputing2(obj = all.data,seurat.obj = TRUE,ICA.type = "JADE",RMT=TRUE)

ICA helped us to identify expression programs for each batch, we further use PAM clustering to group these programs

basal <- CrossBatchGrouping(ica$ica.pooling)

## Identify3 patterns

We use basal programs to find activated module

all.data <- RunICAnet(all.data,basal$ica.filter,PPI.net = PPI)
## [1] "num:303"

RunICAnet could assign a assay class named IcaNet to the Seurat object, we further used module-cell acivity matrix to perform visualization and clustering

all.data <- RunPCA(all.data, features = rownames(all.data), npcs = 20, reduction.name = "IcaNetPCA", reduction.key = "IcaNetPCA_", verbose = F) 
ElbowPlot(all.data,reduction = "IcaNetPCA")

Then, UMAP is used for visualization

all.data <- RunUMAP(all.data, reduction = "IcaNetPCA", dims = 1:15, reduction.name = "IcaNetUMAP",  reduction.key = "IcaNetUMAP_") 
p1 <- DimPlot(all.data, reduction = 'IcaNetUMAP', pt.size = 1, group.by = 'batch')
p2 <- DimPlot(all.data, reduction = 'IcaNetUMAP', pt.size = 1, group.by = 'celltype')
plot_grid(p1, p2)

To make comparison, we can check the raw workflow visualize results

DefaultAssay(all.data) <- "RNA"
all.data <- ScaleData(all.data)
## Centering and scaling data matrix
all.data <- RunPCA(all.data, features = rownames(all.data), npcs = 20, reduction.name = "PCA", reduction.key = "PCA_", verbose = FALSE) 
ElbowPlot(all.data,reduction = "PCA")

all.data <- RunUMAP(all.data, reduction = "PCA", dims = 1:15, reduction.name = "UMAP",  reduction.key = "UMAP_") 
p1 <- DimPlot(all.data, reduction = 'UMAP', pt.size = 1, group.by = 'batch')
p2 <- DimPlot(all.data, reduction = 'UMAP', pt.size = 1, group.by = 'celltype')
plot_grid(p1, p2)
